<DOC><DOCNO> AP891017-0096 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1236EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     10-17 0293</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0303</SECOND><HEAD>Students Stage Anti-U.S. Protests</HEAD><BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Hundreds of radical students onTuesday hurled firebombs at riot police and chanted ``Yankee gohome!'' as they denounced President Bush's meeting in Washingtonwith President Roh Tae-woo.   Police fired volleys of tear gas at the 500 students at Seoul'sKunkook University, where demonstrators burned an effigy of U.S.Ambassador Donald Gregg and demanded his recall.   Similar anti-U.S. protests occurred at Wonkwang University inthe southern city of Chonju after police blocked about 200 studentsfrom marching into the streets.   The students demanded an end to close ties between the UnitedStates and South Korea and to efforts by the United States to openSouth Korean markets wider.   Police reported no arrests or injuries.   The protests came as police questioned six radical students forthe torture death of a student suspected of being a police spy. Thestudents surrendered Sunday after confessing to a priest, policesaid.   Police have been on heightened alert since Roh left Sunday forWashington, with security bolstered at U.S. facilities after anattack on Gregg's residence on Friday.   Dissidents and radical students have demanded Gregg's recall,contending he supported South Korea's military rule when he was CIAstation chief in Seoul in the 1970s.   Six radical students armed with firebombs and iron bars brokeinto the ambassador's residence on Friday and hurled homemade bombsat guards and smashed artwork and windows before being overpoweredby police.   Gregg and his wife escaped unhurt and left for Washington totake part in the Roh-Bush talks Tuesday.   A U.S. Embassy spokesman said U.S. officials were conferringwith Korean police to determine how security around U.S. facilitiescould be improved to prevent future attacks.</TEXT></DOC>